## Coding/documenting guidelines

* Create a file per feature or related features, split as much as possible in different files;
* add docstrings to all functions to explain what they do;
* start each file with a long comment explaining in detail what the feature is about and the different use cases;
* maintain a `Design.md` document at the root of the app that documents all the features of the app;
* log as info all function calls (with their parameters) and log all genai calls with all their parameters (model used, prompt, config) and their outputs, just strip inline data;
* group all configurable items (like model names) in a centralized file;
* always create a way to test the scripts without altering the data;


## Using Lyria models

Here is a complete guide on how to use the Lyria models to generate audio using the `@google/genai` JavaScript SDK.

### 1. Setup and Initialization
First, you need to import the required classes from the SDK and initialize the client with your API key.

```typescript
import { GoogleGenAI, Modality } from "@google/genai";

// Initialize the SDK with your API key
const ai = new GoogleGenAI({ apiKey: process.env.API_KEY });
```

### 2. Choosing the Right Model
The application uses two distinct Lyria models depending on the desired track length:
* **`lyria-3-pro-preview`**: Used for full-length tracks (referred to as "Lyria Pro" in the app).
* **`lyria-3-clip-preview`**: Used for shorter, 30-second clips (referred to as "Lyria Clip").

### 3. Formatting the Input
You can provide text instructions and even combine them with an image to guide the generation. 

* **Text Prompting**: The app structures prompts by stating the duration, the musical context, and specific lyrics instructions (e.g., whether to use custom lyrics, generate timing markers, or make it strictly instrumental).
* **Image Prompting**: If using an image to influence the sound, you pass it as `inlineData` alongside the text prompt inside a `parts` array.

```typescript
const promptText = `Generate a 30-second track. \nContext: "A cinematic track". \nGenerate lyrics with precise [seconds:] timing markers.`;

// For text-only generation
const contents = promptText; 

// OR, for multimodal generation (Text + Image)
const multimodalContents = { 
  parts: [
    { text: promptText }, 
    { inlineData: { data: "BASE64_IMAGE_DATA", mimeType: "image/jpeg" } }
  ] 
};
```

### 4. Calling the Model (Streaming)
Because audio generation can take time, the application streams the response using `generateContentStream`. You must specify `Modality.AUDIO` in the configuration to ensure the model returns audio data.

```typescript
const responseStream = await ai.models.generateContentStream({ 
  model: 'lyria-3-pro-preview', // or 'lyria-3-clip-preview'
  contents: contents, 
  config: { 
    responseModalities: [Modality.AUDIO] 
  } 
});
```

### 5. Processing the Stream
The models return a multimodal response stream containing both the text (lyrics and metadata) and the encoded audio chunks. You need to accumulate both as the stream progresses.

```typescript
let audioAccumulator = ""; 
let textAccumulator = ""; 
let mimeType = "audio/wav"; 

for await (const chunk of responseStream) {
  const parts = chunk.candidates?.[0]?.content?.parts;
  if (!parts) continue;
  
  for (const part of parts) {
    // 1. Extract Audio Chunks
    if (part.inlineData?.data) { 
      if (!audioAccumulator && part.inlineData.mimeType) {
        mimeType = part.inlineData.mimeType; 
      }
      audioAccumulator += part.inlineData.data; 
    }
    
    // 2. Extract Lyrics & Metadata
    if (part.text) {
      textAccumulator += part.text;
    }
  }
}
```

### 6. Converting Base64 to Playable Audio
Once the stream completes, the `audioAccumulator` will contain a massive base64 string. To play it in the browser, you must decode it into a binary format and create a Blob URL.

```typescript
// Decode the base64 string
const binaryString = atob(audioAccumulator);
const len = binaryString.length;
const bytes = new Uint8Array(len);

for (let i = 0; i < len; i++) {
  bytes[i] = binaryString.charCodeAt(i);
}

// Create a Blob and generate a playable URL
const blob = new Blob([bytes], { type: mimeType });
const audioUrl = URL.createObjectURL(blob);

// Play the audio
const audio = new Audio(audioUrl);
audio.play();
```